<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="557" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,838,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">Discussion.</emphasis>
The damaged and obviously later reattached 
<taxonomicName box="[863,980,838,863]" class="Malacostraca" family="Portunidae" genus="Helenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesiformis">
<emphasis box="[863,980,838,863]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">hesiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[990,1093,838,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">lectotype</typeStatus>
specimen is of lighter colour than the 
<typeStatus box="[248,351,874,899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[388,478,874,899]" class="Malacostraca" family="Portunidae" genus="Helenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
<emphasis box="[388,478,874,899]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="557">hirsutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however the colouration is variable in the material examined and cannot be used for separating taxa. No groove but a shallow median depression along pro- meso- and metasternum is present, therefore the “much deeper groove along the sternum and venter” hypothesized by Champion is not characteristic. Differs from the other two species as indicated in the key.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
